><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Part I</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">External spend in local government is some £50 billion per annum and will often be the most significant area of activity of many upper tier Councils. Having a management strategy to deliver effective and efficient business outcomes from that spend is essential.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ability to analyse, compare, evaluate and focus management activity on external spend and supply chain management is an essential element of an effective management of any Council’s resources.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Developing capacity, knowledge and competence to manage demand is essential in all services but particularly in Adult Social Care and Children’s Services.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Markets do not recognise sovereignty. Failure to design procurement capacity and processes to react to different markets and their behaviour, will always lead to a less than optimum position for individual local authorities.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC has had the privilege of being involved in several national procurement leadership improvement programmes. In particular, the work of the CLG sponsored National Improvement and Efficiency Partnership for Construction and Asset Management (the NIEP) illustrated the clear benefits of Council led collaboration for key spend categories. More recently, HCC has also led and concluded the LGA National Procurement Strategy development.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has in the past 12 months translated the wide learning from these national programmes into its own organisation, to help meet its own savings pressures. Key actions have included the following, which we recommend to the committee as practical actions of potential interest to other Councils: </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creation of dedicated strategic capacity to review procurement, commissioning and buying</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undertaking an independent annual procurement capability review</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creating a new Corporate Management Team level External Spend Group to drive improvements and savings</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exploring a spend comparator model across Councils</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creating additional capacity with the private sector to build capacity, import skill and ideas for innovation</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creating an organisational wide model for transformation, “Transforming the Council for 2015” (TtC 2015), that is based on clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> member and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Corporate Management Team </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibility for meeting a specified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> savings level, which includes a key workstream for external spend</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adopting an ‘invest to save’ approach for external spend workstreams</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stressing the collective management of external spend rather than “led by procurement” and the behavioural tensions this can potentially lead to in adopting a departmental view.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Part II</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Committee has decided to carry out an inquiry into local government procurement and invites written submissions from interested parties. The central focus of the inquiry will be to assess the extent to which it is delivering good value for money and meeting the objectives of local authorities. The inquiry will highlight and examine good practice and initiatives within local authority procurement and elsewhere and explore how and to what extent local authorities can adopt and take advantage of them. To assist those making submissions the Committee has identified the following topics that it may cover, though the list is not exhaustive. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent is local government procurement organised to deliver value for money and social, economic and environmental objectives, including stimulating the local economy? To what extent are local authorities achieving the involvement of local residents in delivering value for money? To what extent are local authorities able to develop long-term relationships with contractors?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At an individual Council level, procurement organisational models vary widely from centralised “command and control” to fully de-centralised front line departmental models. HCC has moved to a “centre – led” model over recent years and focused on developing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">right behaviours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and collaborative internal working as being ultimately more important to outcomes than different structural models. This is particularly the case with regard to the broader aspects of commissioning, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">category management and contract / supplier relationship management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. HCC is currently further strengthening its collective performance in these areas through creating dedicated improvement leads, assisted by external partners. Additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">strategic capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has been created to own and drive these improvements: key actions include the following: </span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undertaking an independent annual procurement capability review and associated improvement plan </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creating a new Corporate Management Team level External Spend Group to drive improvements and savings</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exploring a spend comparator model across Councils</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">created additional procurement capacity by utilising the County Council’s Private Sector Partnership (PSP), Deloitte to help bring challenge, market innovation and new ideas for HCC’s consideration</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">embedding external spend as a key workstream within the organisational wide model for transformation, “Transforming the Council for 2015” (TtC 2015), that is based on clear Corporate Management Team responsibility for meeting a set savings level</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adopting an invest to save approach for all TtC 2015 external spend workstream</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stressing the collective management of external spend rather than “led by procurement” and the behavioural tensions this can potentially lead to</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC also has a strong focus on supporting policy through procurement; this applies clearly to promoting local economic benefit. For example, management information is used to track and encourage SME and local spend; practical help is given to smaller suppliers in bid writing and understanding necessary processes; and removing barriers to access is on-going, for example recently adopting a much simpler pre-qualification process. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At a cross – Council level, individual organisations are increasingly working together, as capacity is lost. HCC may be unusual in investing in procurement capacity during these difficult times. Demand for highly effective and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">commercially astute procurement resource</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has argu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ably never been higher,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as demand for higher and sustainable savings continues. This theme of capacity and collaboration is developed further in our response to Question 2. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With regard to the extent to which HCC is involving residents in delivering value for money, this is well illustrated within our Adult Services area. Throughout the procurement lifecycle residents are engaged: PIN notices involve clients and carers in their preparation; consultation with clients occurs at both specification and tender question / evaluation setting stage; finally, monitoring and feedback from contracted services inform contract management and future service shaping.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regarding HCC’s ability to develop long-term relationships with contractors, our performance continues to strengthen. HCC’s learning, particularly in the property arena, of the benefits of creating a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">more collaborative and integrated supply chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, rather than the more traditional fixed price lowest bid approach has delivered proven improved outcomes. OJEU constraints continue to hamper effective procurement in some areas: the UK feels more risk adverse compared with other European countries and arguably pays a heavy cost for this. Notwithstanding this, HCC is further improving its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">contract and supplier relationship management approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as part of the procurement capability improvement plan. This improvement is also likely to involve formal negotiation strategy planning for key existing contracts. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a balance to be found sometimes in local government between larger long term contracts and SME and local supplier support. HCC promotes a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">blended approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, where smaller contracts are best served by SME and local suppliers. Larger and more specialist contracts tend to be procured from larger suppliers, who have the necessary capacity and skills. These are often procured via a collaborative framework. HCC also strongly encourages these larger suppliers to demonstrate their practical support of the local economy through their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">supply chain management leverage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, through using SME and local sub-contractors, as well as apprentices, wherever practicable. Following the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">independent capability review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, HCC are considering the benefits of reducing the relatively high number of suppliers that they currently employ, in a way that would still support the local economy. This would also enable HCC to be able to better contract manage by having a more manageable number of providers. This lead accountable provider model is likely to be initially explored in the social care arena. Any such model, if advanced, would have the requirement to develop and evidence local economic benefit through active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">supply chain management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Allied to these considerations is a move to increased outcome based commissioning including consideration of the “total cost of ownership” of service costs – home care may be a relevant spend category to explore the benefits and feasibility of this market shaping approach.       </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regarding the exploitation of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, HCC believes that economic and capacity pressures are driving an increasing take up across the sector. This is welcome as the market has long rightly complained about the need for a consolidation of collaborative frameworks. In many cases, the right answer for a Council is to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">access an existing framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, including one from central government rather than create a new one.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC itself is passionate about joining forces with others to become a more informed and powerful client, wherever possible. HCC has a strong reputation for leading collaboration in construction and asset management, most recently through the NIEP; a copy of the programme outcomes is attached below:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><a href="http://www.niepbuiltenvironment.org.uk/NIEP%20Programme%20and%20Achievements.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.niepbuiltenvironment.org.uk/NIEP%20Programme%20and%20Achievements.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC are currently working to create a new cross – regional collaborative construction framework for Southern England. In relation to more corporate categories HCC also chairs the Central Buying Consortium (CBC). Finally, HCC has recently led and concluded the LGA National Procurement Strategy, this being informed by the development of both the Quick Wins and Big Wins Procurement Strategies, copies of which are attached below:  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="102" height="66" alt="" /></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">      </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><a href="http://www.niepbuiltenvironment.org.uk/BigWins.html" target="_blank"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.niepbuiltenvironment.org.uk/BigWins.html</span></a><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><a href="http://www.niepbuiltenvironment.org.uk/documents/PCSAWorkstream-QuickWinsStrategyOct2010.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.niepbuiltenvironment.org.uk/documents/PCSAWorkstream-QuickWinsStrategyOct2010.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At a more local level, HCC has recently developed two innovative shared procurement arrangements: firstly, with Hampshire Constabulary and Hampshire Fire and Rescue Services for all common spend categories; and second, with Surrey CC and Reading BC for all property and assets related categories. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regarding information on the operation of PFI contracts within local government, this is not a route generally taken by HCC. There is much widely available commentary on the potential pitfalls of such a route, particularly in the early days of its usage by the wider public sector. The only PFI usage by HCC has been for a street lighting contract awarded in 2010 to Scottish and Southern Energy. This is a 25 year, £120m PFI arrangement allowing replacements and upgrades to Hampshire’s 150,000 street lights and illuminated signs and bollards. Key project benefits include the investment in latest technology, more efficient use of energy, improved visibility and reduced light pollution at night and safer streets with reduced crime. This procurement route allowed HCC to secure the required funds for the programme, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">share risks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> appropriately and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">exploit technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to save energy and cut carbon emissions. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can local authorities access the skills, expertise and capabilities to implement effective procurement strategies, including value for money and social and economic objectives? More specifically, does local government have sufficient understanding of its procurement expenditure and the markets for goods and services to deliver quality procurement strategies—locally and regionally. If not, how can deficiencies be addressed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-33pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-33pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Approaches for individual Councils to access the required skills and capacity could take make forms, depending on their situation and perceived capability gap. HCC found that undertaking a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">regular independent capability review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> gave them an objective and structured view of their own skills and capability gaps. This then allowed HCC to plan its next stage of improvement; HCC see this as a vital and on-going improvement process. Once the capability gap(s) have been identified, the most appropriate route(s) to close the gap can be considered and actioned. For HCC for example, currently this has primarily taken the form of internal up-skilling a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd targeted support from our private sector partner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For Councils generally consideration of accessing the capacity of others may also be a sensible option. In many cases the existing infrastructure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(if effective) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of regional procurement legacy hubs is ideal for this purpose. These hubs are well placed to develop programmes of work across multiple Councils bringing incremental benefit. The construction hubs are an excellent example of this, their open book tendering lending themselves to valuable cost comparisons. In addition, shared procurement arrangements across local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Councils and public bodies can increasingly provide the required capacity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government should consider how it incentivises this behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With regard to spend and market knowledge, existing spend data is generally at a reasonable level. Obviously this will vary across Councils. In HCC we are improving the coding of spend categories to improve our understanding; however, simply raising the visibility of common and category spend across departments has brought benefit, even without 100% accuracy. We are also exploring spend comparative modelling with other Councils. Increasingly HCC is focusing on forecasting future demand against cost predictions to inform our transformation programme. Market knowledge is clearly vital for effective sourcing strategies and capacity constraints can sometimes impede this. At HCC, one of the key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">improvement plans is developing the application of robust category planning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – this will include a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">deep market review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, plus on-going market dialogue to maintain currency. In addition, this market knowledge can be supplemented by regional and national collaboration, sharing knowledge across Councils. Indeed, one of the primary recommendations from the National Procurement Strategy was the formation of individual Councils leading key spend categories and thereby raising collective market knowledge; the HCC led NIEP model illustrates how this has recently worked in the construction and asset management category for example.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Understanding markets and their behaviour is a prerequisite for the design of future collaboration and management activity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent is risk in local government procurement and contracting understood and managed and contracting strategies adopted, which are tailored to product and supplier market places? More specifically, do local authorities maintain and operate effective client management functions and have they entered contractual arrangements which allow the flexibility to meet changing circumstances such as budget reductions or changes in the way a service has to be delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Risk management capability is still maturing in local government compared to the private sector. Arguably, the realities of public accountability and reputational risk act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to reduce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">risk appetite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> across the wider public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sector. HCC are using their private sector partner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to help them increase commercial acumen across the organisation. The response to Question 1 referenced the risk aversion around OJEU. In order to improve risk management, HCC have developed risk assessments to formally analyse procurement risk, to ensure that all decisions are “risk aware” decisions. These assessments are also guided by a strong desire by HCC to be seen as an expert and trustworthy client by the market. Some of the required improvements in risk management are cultural and wider than the scope of procurement or any one Council. In order to respond to these broader issues, HCC is developing a Workforce Development Plan to help drive more commercial acumen across the organisation.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With regard to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">effectiveness of client management functions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a known risk for Councils is the outsourcing of control together with the actual service. As fiscal pressures build, the temptation to “move a problem out” by outsourcing, without fully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">considering the intelligent client function can bring un-intended consequences. Equally, in a similar way to broader more integrated supplier services, “going up the supply chain” and carrying out some previously client functions can make good business sense. Residual departmental defensiveness around this “boundary” will inevitably be overtaken by financial pressures.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regarding the flexibility of contractual arrangements to support necessary change, newer contracts are much more flexible and encourage innovation and continuous improvement, sometimes supported with risk and reward mechanisms. Often, procurement staff play a pivotal role with having a “foot in both camps” – using their supplier relationships to deliver innovation and new ideas to their client organisations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">It is for senior management within Councils to ensure a framework exists to continually improve client side management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How is regularity and propriety of procurement secured and are the arrangements for detecting and addressing impropriety and fraud effective? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC’s approach to securing regularity and propriety of procurement is secured through the following key controls: </span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regular off and on-contract monitoring is reporting to senior officer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local standing orders require contracts over £100K to be let centrally by Legal Services, set out the process to be followed, any potential exception to the process and the various financial limits. Standing orders also require a clear audit trail of the process followed</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">procurement staff are always involved in higher value and risk tendering</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all spend is managed via the corporate ERP system with electronic workflow approvals of purchase orders by local budget holders</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a regular programme of internal audit projects</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the OJEU regulations requiring publication of evaluation criteria and ability of bidders to challenge assists with ensuring regularity and probity</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the officers’ code of conduct requires interests to be declared and governs officers’ relationships with suppliers</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is nationally recognised that fraud can occur at any point in the procurement process. The key areas of external fraudulent activity during the procurement stage can include:</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collusion between staff and bidders to award contracts and specify favourable terms and conditions</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">collusion between bidders to agree that they will not bid competitively for a particular contract and  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bidders failing to tender in accordance with contract specifications and then submitting false claims for extra costs under the contract</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Following the award of the contract, fraud can occur when contractors:</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide inferior goods and services</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">intentionally override minimum statutory pay and health and safety regulations for financial gain</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">present false invoices</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide inflated performance information to attract greater payments than are due</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The approach to effectively manage out impropriety and fraud centre on the following:</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">audit staff with specialist training / qualifications in procurement and contract audit supported by qualified internal audit fraud officers</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a zero tolerance culture to fraud – with top level commitment</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective whistle-blower arrangements in place</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">annual internal audit reviews of procurement and contract management</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proactive fraud reviews targeted at key fraud risks</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school thematic reviews ensuring coverage of procurement risk</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">compliance with corporate standards</span></li><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contract standing orders</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">constitution</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financial procedure rules</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">codes of conduct</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective (and communicated) anti fraud and corruption policy / strategy</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 108pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assurance regarding key processes</span></li><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">declarations of interest</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gifts and hospitality registers</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective segregation of duties</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delegated powers</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear roles and responsibilities</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">due diligence</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disaggregation</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 100.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contract management (including invoicing, performance management and on-going due diligence)</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is local authority procurement fully transparent, audited effectively and does it provide appropriate mechanisms for redress? Specifically, are the arrangements for securing the accountability of procured services and goods to local authorities and local residents adequate and effective? More specifically, to what extent are local authorities able to provide assurance to central government that value for money (in the broadest sense of the term) is delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HCC’s approach to providing transparency, audit controls, mechanisms for redress and accountability centre on the following controls</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sufficient levels of transparency for higher value procurement, certainly over OJEU threshold and locally for contracts over £100K. This includes the publication of contract information, OJEU procedures (including contract notices)</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a regular programme of internal audits</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">redress mechanisms as per OJEU processes</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local corporate complaints procedures for lower value procurements</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">executive member accountability through procurement approvals processes</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In terms of assurance on delivering broad value for money, HCC considers its procurement management approach, continuous improvement culture and controls highlighted in this submission as sound business “input” indicators. Ultimately, however, it is the delivery of outcomes for residents that are the best indicators of success, both in terms of customer satisfaction and Council Tax cost. HCC’s performance remains high in these key areas and it will strive hard to build on this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">By adopting this approach (and others) identified in this response, local authorities will have created a sustainable framework of issues to ensure value for money. Consistently challenging the framework and the issues ensures value for money is sustained. Capacity, competence, challenge and collaboration should be evident in any approach.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Part III</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> – Recommended areas for further review and analysis</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A serious i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nquiry into local government procurement will bring forward a range of responses from commentators and local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Work locally and nationally would suggest that the following topics are also essential for success:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how and what</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> form of leadership model is consistent and capable of working across (local) government</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective collaboration challenges markets and changes their dynamic in favour of the ‘purchaser’</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">management capacity, competence and commercial acumen and effective design and management of supply chains are common themes in private sector procurement</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">procurement activity needs to be aligned with other management activity and seen as a corporate good</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">today’s ‘best deal’ quickly becomes yesterday’s ‘bad deal’ in dynamic markets. Sustaining behaviour and activity across all parts of local government will become a greater challenge.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>